    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> Strategy<br>
	This deck hasnt been battle tested, its all theoretical. Try it and let me know how good (or bad) it is.<br>
	Shadow first, typical Nazgul beating, just pile them on. I dont think theres anything special.<br>
	Now, fellowship This is my wildest idea. To have Sam take Frodos place. The overall idea is to run. So the sites have all the lowest shadow numbers, and in the end, use Thrors Map to switch them on. Given 2 No Strangers, theres only about 60 to 70 twilight for your opponents to use, if you play every card in the deck. Thats not much, given how buff Gondor is.<br>
	Now, the core idea is to go straight to site 4. To do this, let Frodo die at site 4. This way, Sam, who came out at site one when you bid six or seven, can take over. Dont be so quick to remove burdens, take Frodo down to five burdens for emergencies, thats all. Given the running, if Nazguls come out site two and three and following, just assign the buffest to Frodo, he can take on say the Witch King and Attea =). If necessary, site 3 can be Frodos tomb, and heal using Aragorn and Athelas going to site 4. With Nazguls pounding, I doubt if anyone can catch up. Now the Bridge is a bit tricky, its arbitrary if you want to jump to the sanctuary. And then from there on its a lot easier, since hopefully Thrors Map is out, and you just skip across the rest of them. <br>
	A few points, first, since Frodo is to die, the hobbit sword dont go to him, Merry buffs up to seven, and Sams got sword and bounder to keep going. With the massive weapon display, there should be no problem dispatching Isengard and Ringwrath, and Aragorns Bow and PATHS is machine gun to the orcs. The thing to watch out is that no one burdens out. Sam can keep up somewhat with his ability and getting healed by Aragorn. Other healings and condition removals are done by the athelases.<br>
	Weaknesses: first, too big of a deck, for the well-rounded protection, theres almost 80 cards. Since you are running, there arent as many chances to draw. So the more opponents the better, lets you cycle cards faster. Next, because of the already large deck, condition removal cards arent in. Given the powers of Gondor, hopefully it isnt that much of a problem.<br>
	Please critic accordingly, thank you.<br>
